WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.109 --> 00:00:02.692
(bright music)

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.750
- So we often get the question,

00:00:13.750 --> 00:00:16.280
if somebody can use separate handles

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:19.090
as an accessory with X3.

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:22.540
There are little handles
that I guess something

00:00:22.540 --> 00:00:26.983
can replace a bar and hook on to banding.

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:33.080
Which is not a possible thing
for a number of reasons.

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:36.200
I'm gonna explain all those reasons.

00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:37.780
Number one,

00:00:37.780 --> 00:00:41.670
when I talk about keeping
the wrists neutral

00:00:41.670 --> 00:00:42.680
when you're holding the bar,

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:44.810
or when you're holding the bar like this,

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:48.840
when we wanna keep the wrists protected.

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:51.810
You want a continuous bar
that connects both hands

00:00:51.810 --> 00:00:53.510
'cause they balance each other.

00:00:53.510 --> 00:00:56.370
When you separate, this can happen,

00:00:56.370 --> 00:00:57.830
you can twist your wrist

00:00:57.830 --> 00:01:00.240
and some of the smallest
bones in the body,

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:04.400
outside the ear, are right
here and in the ankles

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:07.220
and this X3 is designed to protect you

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:08.710
from that sort of twisting.

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:12.230
So that issue is not fixed

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:14.440
when you have separated handles.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:18.650
Now, this also coincides
with some research

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:20.930
that shows that people
that train with dumbbells

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:22.750
and people that train with barbells,

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:26.483
the ones that train with dumbbells
activate 20% less muscle.

00:01:27.710 --> 00:01:30.980
So, when looking at that research,

00:01:30.980 --> 00:01:32.720
like if you activate 20%, less muscle,

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:34.480
obviously, you're missing out on 20%

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:37.620
of what you could possibly be stimulating.

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:42.470
But there's also sort of a basic idea

00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:45.930
where when you look at a human,

00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:49.290
and if that human has to
pick up something heavy,

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.930
that heavy object is gonna
be grabbed with both hands.

00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:54.690
It's like if you have
something heavy to pick up,

00:01:54.690 --> 00:01:56.240
you don't put one hand behind your back

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:58.283
and try and lift it up with one hand.

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:00.850
I mean, maybe somebody
out there would do that

00:02:00.850 --> 00:02:02.630
but that wouldn't be smart,

00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:06.240
because of the size of the
musculature in each arm

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:08.210
and it doesn't really match

00:02:08.210 --> 00:02:10.720
what's going on in the lower body.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:13.040
You also have to think about balancing.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:15.700
It doesn't make a lot of sense

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:18.783
to necessarily train both
legs at the same time.

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.110
Because humans walk on one leg at a time,

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:24.110
and we run on one leg at a time.

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:25.793
So unless you're a kangaroo,

00:02:26.790 --> 00:02:29.690
training one leg at a
time makes perfect sense.

00:02:29.690 --> 00:02:34.620
Which is why we have everyone
graduate to single leg squats.

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:37.380
But when it comes to the upper body,

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:40.530
the combined strength
of the entire upper body

00:02:40.530 --> 00:02:42.340
can match one leg.

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:43.560
That's where the balances is.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.540
So you pick up something heavy,

00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:47.990
and then you can march
on one leg at a time

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:49.600
with that heavy object.

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:52.000
You wouldn't pick up two
heavy objects at once.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:53.210
If you have heavy objects to pick up,

00:02:53.210 --> 00:02:54.530
you use both hands pick up one,

00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:57.470
you use both to pick up the next one.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:03:00.673
I did a Falsehoods of Fitness
video with Chris Bell,

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:03.410
not that long ago and I asked him,

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:05.800
strongest people in the
world, what do they use?

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:06.870
Barbells or dumbbells?

00:03:06.870 --> 00:03:08.227
And he said, barbells.

00:03:10.140 --> 00:03:12.510
I didn't discuss any
science with him beforehand

00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:16.700
and I didn't precondition
him for the question.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.640
But yes, they use barbells

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:21.960
because barbells make you stronger,

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:23.450
dumbbells really don't.

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:26.423
And so separating the hands,

00:03:27.735 --> 00:03:29.990
it's not what you wanna do.

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:31.830
Now, we do have one exercise

00:03:31.830 --> 00:03:33.760
where we don't use the bar or the plate,

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:35.470
and that's the crossover.

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:38.460
That's because to really
get the hardest contraction

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:39.293
of the pectoral,

00:03:39.293 --> 00:03:41.090
and this is really just
an aesthetic movement.

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:42.210
There's nothing functional about it.

00:03:42.210 --> 00:03:44.680
So if you want the biggest pectorals,

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:45.840
you do the chest press,

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:49.240
and then you might wanna immediately go

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.500
and kind of super set the exercise

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:54.370
with a crossover where you
throw the band around your back

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:57.760
and you do this to get
the hardest contraction

00:03:57.760 --> 00:03:59.650
right here in the pectoral

00:03:59.650 --> 00:04:03.090
because while this is
considered fully contracted,

00:04:03.090 --> 00:04:07.400
this is an even greater
contraction of the pectorals.

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:10.610
But of course you can't do
chest press going across.

00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:14.600
So what we do is just
isolate the pectorals

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:16.480
for that particular movement.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:20.530
So if handles worked, if they were smart,

00:04:20.530 --> 00:04:21.850
I would have much preferred

00:04:21.850 --> 00:04:24.270
to engineer a set of handles over this,

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:26.670
because it would be a
lot easier at airports,

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:29.620
and it would have been a
lot cheaper to manufacture

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:31.140
and cheaper to sell.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:34.010
But it just so happens that
that's not how the body works.

00:04:34.010 --> 00:04:35.330
The body works with bars better,

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:36.473
so we have a bar.

